            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.6-7_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 8, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I've been so much occupied with writing <hi rend="underline">about</hi> you I've had no time to write <hi rend="caps">to</hi> you, but I do want to thank you for the letters, and for the suggestions on Chapter II. I had a feeling Lemmons might be wrong about that Sitting Bull gesture; he thought you invented it. As you say, transferring it from another record doesn't change the point. I'm going to add the Law Wives speech to that chapter, and the account of your lecture to our class is to be jacked up &#8212; it's too colorless as compared to the sparkle of your talks. I'm not going to send you the first draft of Chapter III; I'm going to edit it as soon as it's finished. It's all rehetoric, and I hope you'll like it.</p>
                
                <p>I saw in the <hi rend="underline">Missourian</hi> that Alice and the little girls are moving to Florida. I'm sure it's a fine opportunity, and I'm happy for them, but you will certainly miss them, won't you! I'm sorry to think of them going except for their happiness.</p>
                
                <p>Your letter from Mr. Harmon was good news, and, as you say, pattern. I think more will turn up, and I have a lot of research yet to do before the biography &#8212; the Sioux City paper, and perhaps more letters. I didn't finish in Minneapolis, either. As soon as the dissertation is out of the way I'll get down to business in the biography. The more I work on this the more I am convinced that you and your life and your work should be known to everyone. <del><unclear>It</unclear></del><add>They</add> will be someday, but the sooner the better, I think!</p>
                
                <p>I've been listening to the tapes, and they are really good &#8212; Sandy did an excellent job on them. I was playing the <hi rend="underline">Song of the Indian Wars</hi> one day when the real estate agent who has been showing us homes came by, and she was so fascinated she stayed all morning to listen.</p>
                
                <p>The election to the International Institute of Arts and Letters in Germany is wonderful news. It's a tremendous honor for you, and I'm pleased for you. It's an honor for them, too.</p>
                
                <p>Very soon I'll have a chapter for you, and also I hope to have another visit with Mr. Chaffee before long. If I can borrow a camera I'll take a picture for you; we left our camera in Missouri.</p>
                
                <p>Please give our love to the family, especially to Mrs. Neihardt. It will be good to see you &#8212; only two months now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Lucile Aly</signed>
                </closer>
                
